    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7.0,
      "narration_text": "One electron. One shot. No other electrons. And still \u2014 a wave interference pattern builds up, dot by dot.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Why One Electron Interferes With Itself",
        "sub": "The Tonomura experiment, 1989"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.11,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 7.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "Fire a stream of bullets at a wall with two slits. You get two lumps \u2014 one behind each slit. Bullets add up where they land. No interference.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "note": "Classical: bullets through two slits \u2192 two CRIMSON lumps on detector",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.62,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 17.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "narration_text": "Fire electrons one at a time \u2014 never two at once. Each one hits the detector as a single point. No wave visible. How can there be fringes?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
        "headline": "If each electron is a single particle,\nwhere does the interference pattern come from?",
        "sub": null
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.09,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 26.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "narration_text": "A classical particle has a definite path. Through slit A or slit B \u2014 not both. Two detectors, zero interference. That is what classical physics predicts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "note": "Classical particle: trajectory arrows through either slit A or B; no fringes; CRIMSON two-lump pattern",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.29,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 35.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "Each electron is also a wave. Louis de Broglie: matter has a wavelength, \u03bb = h/p. The electron's probability amplitude passes through both slits simultaneously \u2014 and the two wavefronts interfere.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "note": "TEAL wave amplitude spreading from source, splitting at two slits, interfering, producing fringes",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.81,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 46.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 6.0,
      "narration_text": "Amplitude first. Probability second.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
        "headline": "The amplitude passes through both slits.\nSquare it to get probability.",
        "sub": "\u03bb = h / p"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.32,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 52.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13.0,
      "narration_text": "Where the wavefronts add up in phase \u2014 bright fringe. Where they cancel \u2014 dark fringe. The electron always lands at one point. But the probability of landing anywhere is shaped by the full interference of its own amplitude through both slits.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "note": "Wave interference pattern on detector; bright and dark fringes labeled; single dot lands in bright region",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.63,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 65.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "After 100 electrons: random-looking dots. After 1,000: structure hints at fringes. After 70,000: a clear alternating pattern. Each individual dot was random. The pattern was not.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "note": "Three screens: 100 dots (random), 1000 dots (hints), 70000 dots (clear fringes) \u2014 TEAL accumulation",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.37,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 76.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 5.0,
      "narration_text": "One electron. Both slits.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE IMPLICATION",
        "headline": "One electron \u2014 both slits at once",
        "sub": null
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.67,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 81.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12.0,
      "narration_text": "This was done. Tonomura, Endo, Matsuda, and Kawasaki at Hitachi in 1989. Electrons through a biprism, one at a time. 70,000 electrons later: a clean interference pattern. There is no classical reading of this.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "This was done. Tonomura, Endo, Matsuda, and Kawasaki at Hitachi in\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B10.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "note": "STILL\u00b7ai: series of four detector screens accumulating dots, showing buildup from sparse dots to clear interference fringes",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.46,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 93.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "narration_text": "The electron's wave function passes through both slits. The probability of landing at each point is the squared amplitude of the interference. You can't watch which slit it 'really' went through \u2014 that question has no answer.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "note": "Diagram showing wavefronts, both slits, interference; |\u03c8|\u00b2 = fringe pattern; 'which slit?' crossed out CRIMSON",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.62,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 102.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4.0,
      "narration_text": "The de Broglie number.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE EXAMPLE",
        "headline": "50 keV electron \u00b7 \u03bb = 0.0055 nm",
        "sub": "(Tonomura beam energy, illustrative)"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.28,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 106.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 17.0,
      "narration_text": "An electron at 50 keV has kinetic energy 50,000 eV. Momentum p = \u221a(2mK). de Broglie wavelength \u03bb = h/p \u2248 0.0055 nm \u2014 picometer scale. Fringe spacing for 300 nm slit separation: d sin\u03b8 = \u03bb gives \u03b8 \u2248 0.001\u00b0. The pattern is tiny, but measurable.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "note": "Calculation boxes: K=50 keV, p=\u221a(2mK), \u03bb=0.0055 nm; fringe spacing formula; TEAL labels",
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 23.72,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "t_start": 123.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "One electron, one shot, no partner. And still \u2014 both slits, interference, a pattern that only emerges when the wave and the probability are taken seriously. That is quantum mechanics.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "The amplitude passes through both slits.\nThe pattern is the proof.",
        "sub": null
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.957,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-double-slit-self/clips/B14.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-double-slit-self/mp3/beat-B14.mp3"
    },
